import Mathlib
open CategoryTheory

/-
\begin{definition}[Braid groupoid, $\T$]
\label{def:T}
 $\T$ is the \textit{braid groupoid}. Informally,
 it represents braids from the braid group where
 each strand is labeled; two braids can compose
 only when their labels line up.

 Its objects are sequences of \textit{distinct} letters, where
 each letter labels a strand. This is a slight modification of $\K{}$'s
 objects, which allow duplicate letters. Because $\K{}$'s
 object monoid is free, we can
 easily rename strands to make a distinct sequence
 to represent some braid from $\K{}$ in $\T{}.$
 % The first and last
 % braids in Figure~\ref{fig:braid-canon-example} are
 % equivalent words in $\T{}.$
 We often label strands by which box they connect
 to and index them by their total order from
 that box.


$\T{}$'s morphisms are generated by
crossings of two strands.
For any
$\alpha, \beta$ that are
possibly empty sequences of distinct letters
not containing the
letters $c, d,$ there is a generator
$\gen{c}{d}{} : \alpha{}cd\beta
\to \alpha{}dc\beta$
that crosses strand $c$ over strand $d.$ $\gen{c}{d}{p}$
is defined for any sequence $p$ where
$c$ is directly to the left of $d.$ See
Figure~\ref{fig:T-gen}
for an example of $\gen{c}{d}{} : \alpha{}cd\beta
\to \alpha{}dc\beta.$
In the notation of $\K{},$ we would write
$\gen{c}{d}{} : \alpha{}cd\beta
\to \alpha{}dc\beta$ as
$\id{}_{\alpha} \otimes \sigma_{[c],[d]} \otimes \id{}_{\beta}.$

% \begin{figure}[h]
%     \centering
%     \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{figs_not_from_python/alpha-x-y-beta.pdf}
%     \caption{Diagrammatic
%     representation of $\gen{c}{d}{} : \alpha{}cd\beta \to \alpha{}dc\beta$
%     for $|\alpha| = 3, |\beta|=5.$
%     The strands in $\alpha, \beta$ do not move,
%     and only $c, d$ cross.}
%     \label{fig:T-gen}
% \end{figure}

Note that the domain and the crossed strands $c, d$ uniquely
determine the codomain. Hence
for some sequence of strands $p$ that contains $[c, d],$
we can describe a
unique generator $\gen{c}{d}{p}.$
When context allows, we omit the object
$p$ and refer to some class of generators
$\gen{c}{d}{},$ which all cross $c$ over
$d$ but differ in the strands to the left
and right of $c, d.$
The identity braid (no crossings)
for any sequence object
$p$ is denoted as $\id{}_p : p \to p$.  Similarly, we denote
an identity morphism, regardless of object, with
$\id{}.$

 $\T$ has commutative diagrams
 (the category-theoretic analog of the
 equations in the presentation of a
 group) for
 the shift-past commuting relation
 $$
  \gen{a}{b}{} ; \gen{c}{d}{}
  =
  \gen{c}{d}{} ; \gen{a}{b}{}
 $$
 and the Yang-Baxter equation
 $$
  \gen{a}{b}{}
  ; \gen{a}{c}{}
  ; \gen{b}{c}{}
  =
  \gen{b}{c}{}
  ; \gen{a}{c}{}
  ; \gen{a}{b}{},
 $$ where $a,b,c,d$ are distinct in both. These relations correspond to diagram moves \Btwo{} and
 \Bthree{} respectively, and \Bone{} arises from
 every braid being invertible.
 \end{definition}
-/

-- Implement the braid groupoid. You should follow the same structure
-- as in FreeMonoidal.lean: define the object monoid for a generic type α,
-- then the morphisms, then the commutative diagrams. Because this is the
-- braid groupoid, the extra morphisms will be the σ crossings and inverses,
-- and extra commutative diagrams will be for the commuting, yang-baxter, and
-- inverses. Then provide a named instance of Category, then of MonoidalCategory.

universe u

namespace BraidGroupoid

open MonoidalCategory

